Here's a function in JavaScript that checks if any of the numbers in an array of 5 numbers is a prime number and prints it if it is:
```javascript
function isPrime(arr) {
  for (let i = 0; i < arr.length; i++) {
    let isPrime = true;

    for (let j = 2; j < arr[i]; j++) {
      if (arr[i] % j === 0) {
        isPrime = false;
        break;
      }
    }

    if (isPrime) {
      console.log(arr[i]);
      return;
    }
  }
}

// Example usage:
const arr = [11, 13, 17, 19, 23];
isPrime(arr); // Output: 11
```
This function uses the prime number checking algorithm, also known as the trial division method, to check if a number is prime or not. It first checks if the number is smaller than 2 (not a prime), and then iterates through the numbers 2 to the square root of the number (approximately). If the number is divisible by any of these numbers, it is considered not prime.

To create a simple fake chatbot using HTML, CSS, and JavaScript, you can follow the code below. This code snippet will display a chat history with 4 overall messages: 2 from the bot and 2 from the human. The messages will be displayed in a modal dialog.

1. First, create an HTML file named "index.html":
```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
